Preheat your oven to 200°C. Fill and boil your kettle. Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @ginger{½}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Chop the @vine tomato{2%medium} into 2cm chunks. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all). Halve the @green chilli{½} lengthways, deseed then finely chop.

Pour the boiling water from the kettle into a large #saucepan{} and bring back to the boil with a pinch of @salt{}. When boiling, stir in the @brown basmati rice{150%g} and half the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Cook for ~{25%minutes}. When cooked, drain the rice thoroughly in a #sieve{} and return to the saucepan, off the heat. Cover with a lid to keep warm.

> TIP: Add more water if it starts to evaporate too much.

Meanwhile, pop the @butternut squash{300%g}(diced) onto a lined #baking tray{} and sprinkle over half of the @ground cumin{2%tsp}, a drizzle of @oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Toss to coat the squash well, then arrange in a single layer. Pop on the top shelf of your oven and cook until tender and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #high-sided frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add the onion and cook until soft, stirring occasionally, ~{3-4%minutes}. Mix in the ginger, garlic, @ground turmeric{2%tsp}, @nigella seeds{½%tsp}, remaining cumin, vine tomato and as much chilli as you dare. Cook for ~{1%minute}. Rinse the @red split lentils{100%g} in a sieve then add to the pan. Stir well to coat the lentils then add the @water{600%ml} and remaining stock powder to the pan.

> Bright, delicious, and a rich source of Vitamin A and potassium, butternut squash is a great vegetable to bulk out stews, sauces and curries.

Once everything is ready, stir half the coriander through the dal and season to taste with salt and black pepper if needed. Share the rice between your bowls with the dal spooned on top. Finish with a stack of butternut squash and sprinkle over the remaining coriander. Serve with @baby spinach{125%g}.

> Our warming butternut squash dal with turmeric, ginger, cumin and garlic is the perfect recipe for cosy nights at home. Served with nutty brown rice to keep you feeling full, this wholesome dish is a guaranteed crowd-pleaser.